defdef categorical_barplot(data, categorical_column):
"""
Function to generate a bar plot with percentage labels.
Parameters:
- data: DataFrame
- categorical_column: Categorical column name
"""
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
sns.countplot(x=categorical_column, data=data, palette='viridis')
total_entries = len(data[categorical_column])
forfor p inin plt.gca().patches:
percentage = '{:.1f}{:.1f}%'.format((p.get_height() / total_entries) * 100)
x_position = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2 - 0.1
y_position = p.get_height() + 0.05
plt.text(x_position, y_position, percentage, ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=
10, color='black')
plt.title(f'Bar Plot of {categorical_column}{categorical_column} with Percentage Labels')
plt.show()

defdef bar_plot(data, x_col, hue_col, title):
"""
Function to generate a bar plot for two categorical variables.
Parameters:
- data: DataFrame
- x_col: Column name for the x-axis
- hue_col: Column name for color differentiation (hue)
- title: Title of the plot
"""
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
ax = sns.countplot(x=x_col, hue=hue_col, data=data, palette='viridis', edgecolor='wh
ite')
total_entries = len(data)
forfor p inin ax.patches:
percentage = '{:.1f}{:.1f}%'.format((p.get_height() / total_entries) * 100)
x_position = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2
y_position = p.get_height() + 0.02
# Adjusted y_position to place labels above
bars
ax.annotate(percentage, (x_position, y_position), ha='center', va='bottom', font
size=12, color='black')
plt.xlabel(x_col.capitalize())
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(title=hue_col.capitalize(), loc='upper right')
plt.show()

defdef stacked_bar_plot(data, x_col, hue_col, title):
"""
Function to generate a stacked bar plot for two categorical variables with percentage
labels.
Parameters:
- data: DataFrame
- x_col: Column name for the x-axis
- hue_col: Column name for color differentiation (hue)
- title: Title of the plot
"""
cross_tab = pd.crosstab(data[x_col], data[hue_col], normalize='index')
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
cross_tab.plot(kind='bar', stacked=TrueTrue, color=['pink', 'coral'], edgecolor='white')
# percentage labels
forfor i inin range(len(cross_tab)):
total_entries = cross_tab.sum(axis=1).iloc[i]
forfor j inin range(len(cross_tab.columns)):
percentage = '{:.1f}{:.1f}%'.format(cross_tab.iloc[i, j] * 100)
x_position = i
y_position = cross_tab.iloc[i, :j].sum() + cross_tab.iloc[i, j] / 2
plt.text(x_position, y_position, percentage, ha='center', va='center', fonts
ize=10, color='black',rotation=90)
plt.xlabel(x_col.capitalize())
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title(title)
plt.legend(title=hue_col.capitalize(), loc='upper right')
plt.show()

false negatives is crucial since it minimizes the situations in which the model is unable to identify customers who
are most likely to depart. False negatives are the result of missed chances to take preventative measures, such
as providing incentives to keep consumers and stop them from leaving.

defdef make_confusion_matrix(
cf,
group_names=NoneNone,
categories="auto",
count=TrueTrue,
50/50 [==============================] - 0s 2ms/step
50/50 [==============================] - 0s 1ms/step
200/200 [==============================] - 0s 2ms/step
0.20008567
percent=TrueTrue,
cbar=TrueTrue,
xyticks=TrueTrue,
xyplotlabels=TrueTrue,
sum_stats=TrueTrue,
figsize=NoneNone,
cmap="Blues",
title=NoneNone,
):
"""
This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cf using a Seabo
rn heatmap visualization.
"""
blanks = ["" forfor _ inin range(cf.size)]
ifif group_names andand len(group_names) == cf.size:
group_labels = ["{}{}\n\n".format(value) forfor value inin group_names]
elseelse:
group_labels = blanks
ifif count:
group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}{0:0.0f}\n\n".format(value) forfor value inin cf.flatten()]
elseelse:
group_counts = blanks
ifif percent:
group_percentages = [
"{0:.2%}{0:.2%}".format(value) forfor value inin cf.flatten() / np.sum(cf)
]
elseelse:
group_percentages = blanks
box_labels = [
f"{v1}{v2}{v3}{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip()
forfor v1, v2, v3 inin zip(group_labels, group_counts, group_percentages)
]
box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0], cf.shape[1])
# CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
ifif sum_stats:
# Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
accuracy = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))
# if it is a binary confusion matrix, show some more stats
ifif len(cf) == 2:
# Metrics for Binary Confusion Matrices
precision = cf[1, 1] / sum(cf[:, 1])
recall = cf[1, 1] / sum(cf[1, :])
f1_score = 2 * precision * recall / (precision + recall)
stats_text = "\n\n\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}{:0.3f}\n\nPrecision={:0.3f}{:0.3f}\n\nRecall={:0.3f}{:0.3f}\n\nF1 Sc
ore={:0.3f}{:0.3f}".format(
accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score
)
elseelse:
stats_text = "\n\n\n\nAccuracy={:0.3f}{:0.3f}".format(accuracy)
elseelse:
stats_text = ""
# SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
ifif figsize isis NoneNone:
# Get default figure size if not set
figsize = plt.rcParams.get("figure.figsize")
ifif notnot xyticks:
# Do not show categories if xyticks is False
categories = FalseFalse
# MAKE THE HEATMAP VISUALIZATION
plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
sns.heatmap(
cf,
annot=box_labels,
fmt="",
cmap=cmap,
cbar=cbar,
xticklabels=categories,
yticklabels=categories,
)
ifif xyplotlabels:
plt.ylabel("True label")
plt.xlabel("Predicted label" + stats_text)
elseelse:
plt.xlabel(stats_text)
ifif title:
plt.title(title)
# Creating a DataFrame for metrics
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame({
'Metric': ['Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'F1 Score'],
'Score': [accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score]
})
returnreturn metrics_df.T

defdef create_model(layer_1=32, layer_2=16, lr=0.001, dropout_rate1=0.0, dropout_rate2=0.0)
:
# Initializing the neural network
model_3 = Sequential()
# Adding the input layer (by specifying input dimension)
model_3.add(Dense(layer_1, activation='relu', input_dim=X_train.shape[1]))
# Adding dropout before the hidden layer
model_3.add(Dropout(dropout_rate1))
# Adding the hidden layer
model_3.add(Dense(layer_2, activation='relu'))
# Adding dropout after the hidden layer
model_3.add(Dropout(dropout_rate2))
# Adding the output layer
# We have an output of 1 node, which is the desired dimensions of our output (stay wi
th the bank or not)
# We use the sigmoid because we want probability outcomes
model_3.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
# Adding Adam initializer
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr)
# Compile model
model_3.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=[tf.keras.m
etrics.Recall()])
returnreturn model_3
